Lawmakers in Russia voted to allow local hospitals to perform organ transplants, aiming to combat organ trafficking.
Concerns were raised about organs from China being harvested from unwilling donors.
In China, reports implicated hospitals and jails in a transplant scandal involving Falungong prisoners.
Meanwhile, discussions in the Philippines focused on regulating organ donation due to rampant trafficking.
In the US, a debate arose over reducing sentences for prisoners who donate organs.
The closure of a kidney transplant program at Kaiser Permanente sparked investigations into patient safety.
Globally, the need for organ donation laws and regulations was emphasized to address the shortage of organs.
